        <div class="space-y-6">
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What is the first step in selecting an industrial centrifuge?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">The first step is fluid analysis — characterizing the mixture to be separated: phase compositions, particle size distribution, density difference, viscosity, temperature, and required flow rate. Without accurate fluid data, centrifuge sizing and type selection cannot be done reliably.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">How do I choose between a disc stack centrifuge and a decanter centrifuge?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Use a disc stack centrifuge for separating fine particles from liquid-continuous feeds at low solids concentrations (typically under 3% by volume). Use a decanter centrifuge for dewatering high-solids sludges (3–40% solids) where continuous solids discharge is required. Fluid testing can confirm which technology achieves the required separation quality.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">Is a remanufactured centrifuge a good alternative to a new one?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">A remanufactured centrifuge can deliver 80–90% of new machine performance at 40–60% of the cost, provided it is fully rebuilt with new bearings, seals, and wear components and properly balanced. Dolphin Centrifuge offers fully refurbished disc stack and decanter centrifuges with performance documentation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
